<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Eschscholzia</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Lupinus</i> <i>nanus</i> and/or another <i>Eschscholzia</i> species is characteristically abundant in the herbaceous layer with <i>Amsinckia</i> <i>menziesii</i>, <i>Avena</i> <i>barbata</i>, <i>Bromus</i> spp., <i>Chaenactis</i> <i>glabriuscula</i>, <i>Clarkia</i> spp., <i>Eriogonum</i> spp., <i>Erodium</i> <i>cicutarium</i>, <i>Hirschfeldia</i> <i>incana</i>, <i>Hypochaeris</i> <i>radicata</i>, <i>Lotus</i> <i>purshianus</i>, <i>Lupinus</i> <i>bicolor</i>, <i>Rumex</i> <i>salicifolius</i>, <i>Salvia</i> <i>carduacea</i> and <i>Vulpia</i> <i>myuros</i>. Emergent trees and shrubs may be present at low cover, including trees <i>Pinus</i> <i>sabiniana</i> and shrubs:<i>Eriogonum</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Herbs < 0.5 m; cover is intermittent to continuous. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Eschscholzia californica</i> > 50% relative cover in the herbaceous layer; many annual grasses, such as <i>B. hordeaceus</i>, may be common (Kittel et al. 2012).</li>
		
		<li><i>Eschscholzia californica, Lupinus bicolor,</i> and/or <i>L. nanus</i>  > 30% relative cover in the herbaceous layer with a variety of native and non-native forbs and grasses (Klein et al. 2015).</li>
		
		<li><i>Salvia carduacea</i>  > 30% relative cover in the herbaceous layer (cf. Buck-Diaz and Evens 2011).</li>
		
		<li><i>Eschscholzia californica, Lupinus bicolor,</i> and/or <i>L. nanus</i>  > 50% relative cover in the herbaceous layer, > 30% relative cover with a variety of native and non-native forbs and grasses (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Upland slopes or flats. Soils are well drained, sandy to loamy, derived from many substrates, including serpentine, and often have high levels of bioturbation.  </div>
</div>

        
