<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> The genus <i>Eschscholzia </i>involves approximately 12 species of western North America<i>. E. californica </i>is the most widespread species in the genus, extending from southwestern Washington south into the Baja California and east to western Texas. The species is highly variable, including long-lived, prostrate perennials along the coast, erect perennials in inland valleys, and annuals in the interior. The coastal form tends to have yellow flowers, whereas inland forms range from yellow to orange (Leger 2004). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Eschscholzia californica, </i>the state flower of California, has contributed significantly to the iconic vision of the stateâ€™s wildflower displays. Many areas of the state, especially the drier portions of central and southwestern California, experience brilliant poppy displays. Recently, ecologists (Minnich 2008, Schiffman 2007, Wills 2006) have suggested that prior to European influence the dominant plants in dry areas were mainly native forbs, rather than grasses, due to relatively low and unpredictable annual rainfall. <br/>
<br/>
This alliance has been expanded to include additional genera of annual forbs since the Manual's publication in 2009. Lupines, such as <i>Lupinus bicolor</i> and <i>L. nanus</i> fluctuate in abundance from year to year, but often co-occur with poppies.  <i>Salvia carduacea</i> is another annual wildflower that may co-dominate in this alliance. These stands are highly seasonal and are dependent upon favorable rainfall patterns.<br/>
<br/>
This alliance represents one of several annual herbaceous types that are widespread in the southern and central portion of cismontane California, where disturbances such as grazing, fire, occasional flooding, and slope movement are moderately frequent. These stands appear to shift radically year-to-year in species composition depending primarily on the amount and timing of precipitation. <br/>
<br/>
Stands may include <i>E. californica, E. lemmonii, E. caespitosa, </i>and related taxa. Other species, especially the non-natives, may mask <i>Eschscholzia </i>and <i>Lupinus </i>abundance in some years, and competition with nonnative plants is common. Robinson et al. (1995) showed that <i>E. californica </i>competes closely with non-native <i>Bromus diandrus </i>for resources. A study by Cook (1965) suggested <i>E. californica </i>grows principally where <i>Avena fatua </i>cannot exist, as on rocky, steep sites with porous, sterile, or serpentine soils. <i>E. californica </i>is adapted to these conditions through its deep taproot and physiological tolerance to different soil conditions. <br/>
<br/>
We do not completely understand the relationships between this and other herbaceous alliances. <i>E. californica </i> and related taxa appear to tolerate relatively well-drained, disturbed, sandy soils whereas plants of the <i>Lasthenia californica- Plantago erecta-Vulpia microstachys </i>alliance tolerate shallow, skeletal soils; those of the <i>Plagiobothrys nothofulvus </i>alliance tolerate soils with higher moisture content. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
