    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of<i> Eschscholzia</i>, when forming wildflower displays, includes the Northern California Interior Coast Ranges (M261C) and Southern California Coast (261B).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Ac, Aj). Stands of <i>E. californica</i> occur in the East Bay Hills on shallow soils, and stands of <i>E. lemmonii</i> are sometimes showy on steep southerly facing slopes of marine sediments in the inner Santa Lucia Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Aa-f, Ah-k). Stands of <i>E. californica</i> at Pinnacles National Monument (Kittel et al. 2012) characterize the alliance. Most stands are small (< 0.5 ha) and associated with stream channels, steep slopes, and recently burned slopes. Stands of E. caespitosa and <i>E. californica</i> also occur in Monterey and San Luis Obispo Cos., especially in high rain years.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ag, Au-z). Stands occur in the Elk Hills and at the base of the Grapevine and may be very showy in good flower years.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ag). Wildflower displays of <i>E. californica</i> and other herbs occur in the western subsections in high rain years. Some of the most spectacular are in the Antelope Valley at the California Poppy Preserve southwest of Lancaster, where stands also include high cover of <i>Castilleja exserta, Lasthenia californica,</i> and <i>Lupinus bicolor</i> (Clark and Charest 1992).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Ac, Ag, Ai-j, Al-m). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Bb, Be). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fc-e). Stands occur in the San Emigdio Mountains and are showy in the vicinity of the Grapevine.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bc, Bh). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bb, Bj-l). Stands observed in the Lake Matthews area of western Riverside Co. rival those of the western Mojave Desert in high rain years.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Many stands have a history of grazing, trampling, fire, or other recent disturbances. Inventoried stands have moderate to heavy cover of non-natives, which is extreme in some years. We are unclear as to the proper management to emphasize <i>Eschscholzia californica</i>. Schiffman (2007) suggested that the non-native <i>Erodium </i>spp. have ecologies very similar to native annual forbs, including <i>Eschscholzia californica. </i>The non-native <i>Bromus </i>spp. attain stronger dominance in high winter rainfall years (Bartolome et al. 2007a). Clark and Charest (1992) suggested that fire is an important feature in the western Mojave Desert in maintaining stands of herbs. Long periods lacking fire in the California Poppy Preserve appear to lead to higher <i>Ericameria nauseosa </i>cover. 

<i>Eschscholzia californica </i>has been widely planted as a slope stabilizer, as an ornamental, and as a naturalizing landscape item for many years. <i>E. californica </i>has escaped from cultivation. It is often possible to identify native populations by their seed dormancy, which is generally absent in plants of cultivated seed (Clark and Charest 1992). Preserving genetic heritage of seeds is important when conducting restoration, because population differences in seed dormancy and leaf pigmentation may be adaptive (Espeland and Myatt 2001). Managers should collect and plant seeds of the coastal, inland, and annual ecotypes in the appropriate region. </div>
</div>

    

    

